Introduction to C Programming


THEORY EXERCISE

C programming language was developed in 1972 by Dennis Ritchie at Bell Laboratories. It was created to develop the UNIX operating system. Before C, languages like B and BCPL were used, but they lacked efficiency and flexibility. C combined low-level (hardware-level) and high-level features, making it powerful and fast.

Over time, C became one of the most widely used programming languages. It influenced many modern languages like C++, Java, and Python.

Importance of C:

It is fast and efficient
Provides low-level memory access
Used to build system software
Portable across platforms

Why C is still used today:

Used in operating systems (Linux, Windows parts)
Embedded systems and microcontrollers
High-performance applications
Strong foundation for learning programming
LAB EXERCISE

Three real-world applications of C:

Embedded Systems
C is widely used in microcontrollers, IoT devices, and hardware programming.
Operating Systems
Operating systems like UNIX and Linux are written in C.
Game Development
C is used in game engines for performance-critical parts.
